    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok that makes sense. so with CIF, if the ship encounters some major issues during the voyage—like a storm or something that causes cargo to be lost at sea—the risk has already passed to us, right? even though the seller paid for the insurance? help me understand how that insurance claim process actually works for the buyer in that scenario.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, you are correct; once the goods are on board under CIF, the risk of loss or damage during the main carriage shifts to you, the buyer, even though the seller arranged the insurance. The insurance policy is there to cover *your* interests once the risk has transferred.\n\nThe claim process for you, the buyer, is essentially a process of making a claim against the insurance policy the seller procured. You need to notify the insurance company promptly about the loss or damage. The insurance company will then investigate the claim based on the terms of the policy. You'll need to provide documentation—like the bill of lading and proof of loss—to substantiate your claim.",
      "source": "target",
